{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"010b3c54-ddb1-4652-8c0e-9e8fbe706bcd","content":"Here are the MSBuild evaluation performance issues in this project:\n\n## 1. Expensive Property Function — File I/O During Evaluation (line 13)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nCalling `File.ReadAllText` during evaluation forces synchronous disk I/O on every evaluation pass (design-time builds, restores, IDE reloads). This blocks the evaluator.\n\n## 2. Overly Broad Glob (line 9)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\nA recursive wildcard (`**\\*.*`) forces MSBuild to enumerate the entire directory tree on every evaluation. As the repo grows, this becomes increasingly expensive. It also risks pulling in unintended files.\n\n## 3. Deeply Chained Imports (3 levels)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nEach import adds an XML parse + evaluation pass. While 3 levels is modest, this pattern tends to grow over time and makes evaluation graphs harder to cache.\n\n---\n\n**Recommendations:**\n| Issue | Fix |\n|-------|-----|\n| `ReadAllText` | Move file reading to a target (runs at build-time only, not evaluation). |\n| `**\\*.*` glob | Narrow to specific extensions (e.g., `**\\*.txt`) or list files explicitly. |\n| Chained imports | Flatten into fewer files where possible. |\n\nThe biggest offender is **#1** — property functions performing I/O execute every time the project is evaluated (including IDE background evaluations), not just at build time.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a1f0186b-9d9e-4786-ac67-c54adc35fddf","outputTokens":419,"requestId":"0422:5DFE:AFC3A7:CCCA29:69F2AE44"},"id":"ecd2334c-ca65-45ea-beaf-43a824d2670b","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:20:15.601Z","parentId":"8d391ff0-e234-4eeb-9e15-36f944a404cd"}
